[[File:Bones to Peaches icon (mobile).png|left]]
'''Bones to Peaches''' is a [[spell]] that turns all [[bones]] up to and including [[big bones]] in the inventory into [[peach]]es, which can be eaten to heal 8 [[Hitpoints]]. Before it can be cast, it must be unlocked from the [[Mage Training Arena]] for 200 [[Mage Training Arena/Telekinetic Theatre|Telekinetic]] points, 300 [[Mage Training Arena/Alchemist's Playground|Alchemist]] points, 2,000 [[Mage Training Arena/Enchanting Chamber|Enchantment]] points, '''and''' 200 [[Mage Training Arena/Creature Graveyard|Graveyard]] points.

[[Bones to peaches (tablet)|Its tablet form]] is usable without unlocking the spell, albeit granting no experience. However, ''crafting'' the tablet requires the player to have unlocked the spell.

Bones to Peaches is commonly used to extend trips when food is scarce but bones are plentiful, such as in the [[God Wars Dungeon]] or the [[Smoke dungeon]]. Players may also consider the healing effect of [[Guthan the Infested's equipment|Guthan's equipment]] as an alternative (or in addition) to the spell. The tablets can be used to save inventory space instead of bringing the runes required to cast the spell.

[[Demonic ashes]] cannot be converted as they are not considered bones. Attempting to convert bones of a higher tier than big bones gives the message {{RSFont|The bones you're holding aren't suitable for peachifying.}} Attempting to cast the spell without any bones gives the message {{RSFont|You aren't holding any bones!}}

The tablet form of the spell cannot be used inside the [[Creature Graveyard]] in the Mage Training Arena; doing so gives two messages: {{RSFont|This tablet cannot be used on bones from the Mage Training Arena.}}, and {{RSFont|You aren't holding any bones!}} Despite the second message, casting the bones to peaches ''spell'' can convert the bones gathered in the graveyard, only the tablet cannot.

Casting the spell in the [[Al Kharid Palace]] is a hard task in the [[Lumbridge & Draynor Diary]] (using the tablet form of the spell '''does not''' work).

